{"/service/ndnp/idhi/batch_idhi_everglades_ver01/data/sn88056114/0041421194A/1907121401/0104.xml":{"full_text":"A Tariff Created Trust.\nThe persuasive force behind 278 newspapers of all\nshades of political opinion, organized for vigorous\nwarfare, is to be employed against the tariff which\nenables the manufacturers of paper to levy unearned\ntribute on the publishers of newspapers. These\npublishers charge, through their committee, that\n\"unlawful combinations of paper makers have been\norganized recently, that artificial stimulation of\nprices has been accomplished and that judicial pro\nhibition of such efforts has been disobeyed.\"\nA resolution adopted by the organization states\nthat it is the sense of the associated publishers that\nthe duty on printing paper, wood pulp and all ma\nterial entering into the manufacture of printing pa\nper should be immediately repealed.\nThe President of the United States is asked to\ngive attention to the existence of a trade conspiracy\nby which the makers of paper arranged for an ad\nvance of $12 a ton upon paper supplied during the\ncurrent year and an announced advance of an addi\ntional $10 per ton for the next year. These advances\nwill net the paper combine $10,000,000 for the first\nyear and $19,000,000 for the second year.\nThe combination that is able to impose its own\nprices upon consumers was instituted twelve years\nago. The publishers' organization has ascertained\nthat the first step in the conspiracy was taken while\nthe Dingley tariff bill was pending, when the lobby\nists of the embryo trust induced Congress to levy\nheavy duties upon manufactured paper and the\nproducts that enter into the manufacture of paper.\nWith that much accomplished, the completion of\nthe trust was easy and it was soon able to fix the\nprices on all the products of the mills.\nThe evidence of the publishers appears to con\nclusively show that high tariff, protective tariff it is\ncalled, was wholly responsible for the organization\nof the paper trust and that the high tariff that\nkeeps out importations is sustaining the trust.\nThis is the trust that was dissolved by order of\nthe Federal court at St. Paul, but it was speedily\nreorganized on another basis and is preying upon\nthe public with its old-time voracity. The Federal\nDepartment of Justice is asked by the publishers'\norganization to give its attention to what is a prac\ntical violation of the order of the court through\nwhich the intentions of a trust destroying admin\nistration were overcome about as violently as the\nhighwayman accomplishes a job of plundering.\nThe cause of the paper consumers is an interesting\none. If they can ever get into the court of public\nopinion they will be able to convince the country that\nhigh tariff breeds and nurtures trusts and that the\ntrust destroying laws are nullified through the eva\nsion of the edicts of the courts by the representa\ntives of monopolistic combinations.\nThe Past Reviewed.\nIn an article published over his signature in the\nLewiston (Idaho) Tribune, A. F. Parker, of Grange\nville, Idaho, whose Democracy is a matter of record,\ncalls attention to the election of 1892 and the con\nsequences of the subsequent aftitude of the leaders\nof the Democratic party.\nMr. Cleveland was placed in the White House by\nan overwhelming vote and a Democratic Congress\ntook possession of National legislation. Two years\nlater the House Democratic majority was exchanged\nfor a Republican majority, and four years later the\nSenate passed into control of the Republicans, who\nhave since managed all the departments of the Gov\nernment.\nThe Democratic administration and the Democratic\nCongress followed the course marked out for them\nby the representatives of the same interests that have\njust unloaded a panic on the country and ignored\nthe financial and business demands of the constitu\nency of expectant millions that had placed them in\npower.\nIn the course of the Cleveland administration a\nfinancial panic ensued and when the time came to\nelect another President, the Governmental associates\nof \"the interests\" joined in opposition to the choice\nof the Democratic party and defeated him. In his\nown graphic way, Mr. Parker proceeds with the\nrecital\nIt is useless now to chew the rag on the issues\nwhich split the Democratic party wide open and, in\nthe succeeding elections of 1894, reversed the big\nDemocratic majority in the House into an equally\nlarge Republican majority. Undeniably Cleveland\nand his safe and sane Democratic associates were\nsincere in their contentions on behalf of the gold\nstandard and plutocracy; but they certainly did not\nrepresent the rank and file of the Democratic party.\nIn fact the resentment of the rank and file went\nso far as to permanently retire to private life such\nsafe and sane conservative Democrats as Cleve\nland, together with Carlisle and Watterson of Ken\ntucky, Vance and Ransom of North Carolina, Voor\nhees of Indiana, and other equally illustrious Demo\ncrats in and out of Congress who sacrificed their\nown beliefs on financial issues and followed the\nbrazen calf of the gold standard which Cleveland\nCarlisle-Watterson had set up. With the honorable\nexception of Hoke Smith, now Governor of the\ngood old Democratic State of Georgia, every mem\nber of the Cleveland administration antagonized\nBryan in the memorable campaign of 1896, and each\nof them, with the exception noted, have been perma\nnently retired to private life by the indignant and\noutraged Democracy, and all who are now living are\naffiliated with the frenzied financiers who, in 1896,\nclaimed to be the \"defenders of the National honor.\"\nThe public will have to admit that all things\ncame\nto pass as portrayed by Mr. Parker, and in making\nthe admission it will be brought into\nsid\u00e9ration of the immediate past and the unpleasant\npresent. The Republican administration and the\nRepublican Congress have not been responding to\nthe demands of the millions of their constituents and\nopportunity seems ripe for a repetition of the visita\ntion of party punishment that retired to oblivion\nall the Democrats of the Cleveland school.\nFor a time the present administration fought \"the\ninterests\" through an unwilling Congress, but it has\nfinally succumbed to the pressure that wrought such\nan effect on Cleveland and his allies during the per\niod of 1892-96. The administration is helpless in the\nclutches of a panic that may have been produced\nfor that effect\u2014for \"the interests\" are able to create\nserious con\nfinancial crises at will, through their control of the\nsupply of gold.\nOpportunity is ripe for a political revolution that\nmay change the entire complexion of the Govern\nment, executive and legislative.\nRepublican Convention Called.\nChicago secured the Republican National\ntion and June 16th next is the date fixed for the\nopening of the quadrennial session of the presiden\ntial nominating body of the political party\npower.\nand the profit of the gathering\u2014Chicago, Kansas\nCity and Denver\u2014and Chicago was an easy winner,\nconven\nnow in\nThere were three contestants for the honor\nreceiving thirty-one of the votes of the committee,\nto eighteen for Kansas City and four for Denver.\nThe call was issued on Sunday, the 8th inst, by\nthe full committee. It provides that the convention\nshall consist of four delegates at large from each\nState, two delegates for each representative at large,\ntwo delegates from each Congressional district and\nfrom each of the territories of Arizona, New Mexico\nand Hawaii and from the District of Columbia and\nAlaska, Porto Rico and the Philippine Islands. For\neach delegate an alternate may be chosen.\nSuch is to be the composition of the convention.\nThe committee took pains to say that all electors,\nwithout regard to past political affiliation, would be\npermitted to participate in the primary gatherings\nleading up to the selection of delegates to the Na\ntional convention. The delegates are to be chosen\nbetween the 16th of January and the 16th of May\npreceding the date of the convention. These are the\npreliminary arrangements for what will probably\nprove to be one of the most interesting and exciting\nconventions of the Republican party. Eliminating\nMr. Roosevelt from the contest, there is no sem\nblance of a settled purpose in behalf of any one man\non the part of the Republican party.\nIt is weakened by differences of vital importance\nrepresented by its several factions and is staggering\nunder a sudden blow of financial panic. Its mem\nbers have been told so often that no business dis\nturbance could manifest itself under Republican\nmanagement, and the fiction has been so well sus\ntained by accidental circumstances, that a weakening\nof faith treads closely on the heels of the October\nMuch vaunted immunity from commercial\ndisaster cannot now be invoked to delude the voting\npublic into the imagined security of a Republican\nvictory at the polls.\nAmong all the aspirants for the high honor to\nbe conferred by the Republican convention, none has\nyet been able to place more than one or two States\nto his credit and each has strong opposition to en\ncounter in the debatable States. The party has yet\nto concentrate upon a leader wearing the plume of\na McKinley or a Roosevelt and in its distraught\ncondition its annual convention will become a\nmatter of more than passing interest at home and\nabroad.\ncrisis.\nThe Source of Trouble.\nIn a discussion of the troubles that have spread\nthemselves over the country, the Philadelphia North\nAmerican discusses the cause of a condition that\nought not to exist\nThe institutions that are in trouble owe their trou\nbles not to any incidents or accidents of legitimate\nbanking, but to gambling. The disclosures of the\nlast few months are not of new-found evil practices.\nWall street assumes the virtuous pose of being\nshocked by the traction scandal and the use of a\nchain of banks as an adjunct to stock jobbing. These\npractices, known now by the public, have been\nknown for years by Wall street and by well-in\nformed bankers throughout the country. The cover\nis off now, or at least partly lifted. But the malo\ndorous mess that has long been stewing beneath\nis not of new mixing.\nUpon the same subject, an article in the New York\nWorld, contributed by Judge A. J. Dittenhoefer,\nsays\nNow is the time to consider what measures should\nbe taken to prevent the recurrence in the future of\nsuch financial debauchery as has prevailed within\nthe last year or two. The root of the evil lies in\nthe stock exchange ticker. Eradicate the root and\nto a large extent the evil will be eliminated. Every\nday of the year the ticker is made to spread broad\ncast false and fictitious quotations of the value of\ncorporate securities held by the \"high financiers\" to\nenable them to unload on the outside public. They\nmake fake sales, which are run off on the ticker as\ngenuine, and the public, believing that the sales have\nactually been made, are fooled into purchasing them\nat the ticker prices. When the financiers have un\nloaded a sufficient quantity the prices are depressed\nby them in the same manner, to the great loss of\nthe persons who bought them at the fictitious ticker\nprices, and then the financiers buy them back and\nunload them again, and so the endless chain is kept\nup. It is a regular bunco game.\nThe counsel of wisdom suggests that the source\nof woe be abolished. The gamblers of the racing\ncourse, of the roulette wheel and the faro box, rep\nresentatives of small delinquencies, are beset by the\ncontrivances of law and the mandatory commands\nof police systems, while the gamblers that strew\nwreckage over forty-six States are legalized by the\nlaw's consent to their transactions.\nIt is believed by the New York Journal of Com\nmerce that some credit is due the Secretary of the\nTreasury for yielding to an impression of error and\nstopping the sale of the Government certificates of\nindebtedness before he had gone deeply into the\n$100,000,000 he had ordered printed,\nway, the Journal of Commerce expresses its belief\nthat Mr. Cortelyou ought to have sought competent\nadvice, needing himself the training and experience\nthat equips the expert financier. Instead, says the\nNew York paper, \"with the self-confidence of a fail\nure to comprehend, he ventured boldly where angels\nof finance might have feared to tread, or rather\nwould never have thought of treading.\"\nIn a kindly","height":"19344","width":"14976"}}
